# Why `push(...hugeArray)` Crashes But `concat()` Doesn't

## The Core Problem: Spread Operator in Function Calls

When you use `array.push(...hugeArray)`, the spread operator converts the array into individual arguments:

```javascript
// This becomes:
array.push(elem1, elem2, elem3, ..., elem1000000)

// The JavaScript engine must:
// 1. Evaluate ALL arguments first
// 2. Create a call frame on the stack
// 3. Pass them all as separate parameters
```

This exhausts the **call stack** because:
- Each function call adds a frame to the stack
- With 1 million spread arguments, V8 tries to process a massive argument list
- The internal function call mechanism (not the recursive calls) overflows

## Why `concat()` Works

```javascript
// concat() is called ONCE with the array as a single argument
const result = array.concat(hugeArray);

// Implementation: iterates internally without stack frames per element
```

`concat()` handles the array iteration **internally** using a loop, not recursive calls.

## V8 Implementation Differences

### `push(...spread)` - Stack Overflow Path
```cpp
// Simplified V8 pseudocode
void CallFunction(JSFunction* func, int num_args) {
    // num_args = 1,000,000 in our case
    // Each argument needs evaluation on stack
    StackFrame* frame = AllocateStackFrame(num_args);
    // Stack grows linearly with argument count
}
```

### `concat()` - Heap-Based Iteration
```cpp
// concat() iterates using a loop, not function calls
Object* Concat(JSArray* receiver, JSArray* other) {
    // Uses a single stack frame
    for (int i = 0; i < other->length(); i++) {
        // Heap operation, no stack frame per element
        result->elements[pos++] = other->elements[i];
    }
    return result;
}
```

## Practical Demonstration

```javascript
const small = [1, 2, 3];
const huge = new Array(1000000).fill(0);

// ❌ Stack overflow
try {
    small.push(...huge); // RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded
} catch(e) {
    console.log(e.message);
}

// ✅ Works fine
const result = small.concat(huge);
console.log(result.length); // 1000003

// ✅ Also works - chunked pushing
const chunkSize = 1000;
for (let i = 0; i < huge.length; i += chunkSize) {
    small.push(...huge.slice(i, i + chunkSize));
}
```

## Safe Alternatives

```javascript
// 1. Use concat (creates new array)
const result = array.concat(hugeArray);

// 2. Use a loop
for (const item of hugeArray) {
    array.push(item);
}

// 3. Use push with chunked spread
const chunkSize = 10000;
for (let i = 0; i < hugeArray.length; i += chunkSize) {
    array.push(...hugeArray.slice(i, i + chunkSize));
}

// 4. Use splice (in-place)
Array.prototype.push.apply(array, hugeArray); // ⚠️ Also risky
// Better: use a loop or concat

// 5. Spread into loop
const iter = hugeArray[Symbol.iterator]();
for (const item of iter) {
    array.push(item); // One at a time
}
```

## The Argument List Limit

V8 has a hardcoded limit on function arguments:

```javascript
const MAX_ARGS = 65536; // Varies by V8 version

// This will always fail
const arr = new Array(100000).fill(1);
arr.push(...arr); // RangeError before hitting stack

// concat ignores this limit
arr.concat(arr); // No problem
```

## Summary Table

| Method | Stack Usage | Iteration | Limit |
|--------|------------|-----------|-------|
| `push(...arr)` | O(n) - per argument | External | ~65k args |
| `concat(arr)` | O(1) - single call | Internal loop | Heap limited |
| Loop `push()` | O(1) per item | External loop | None |

**Rule**: Never spread huge arrays into function calls. Use `concat()`, loops, or chunked approaches instead.
